Reconstructing Osteosarcoma¶

Here we attempt reconstruction of osteosarcoma spatial expression using MERFISH data. We see:

  1. denovo reconstruction does not work. We show why.
  2. using a few marker genes we get good reconstruction
  3. joining both terms of smoothness assumption and atlas can still help ?

Denovo Reconstrustion¶

Setting up for reconstruction ... done ( 0.33 seconds )
Reconstructing spatial information with 0 markers: 645 cells and 645 locations ... 
It.  |Err         
-------------------
    0|1.007855e-03|

Why did it not succeed?¶

Denovo reconstruction relies on preservation of distances between: (1) pairs of cells in terms of expression (2) pairs of locations in terms of physical distance

Weak Correlation of Exp,Loc Distances¶

Although this data is composed of a single cell-type, factors that are not spatially "smooth", meaning nearby cells share similar expression, may be dominating (e.g. cell-cycle).

Weak Correlation of Exp,Loc Costs¶

Since we assume distances are more preserved at smaller distances (e.g. physically close cells <-> similar expression), instead of using the L2 distance between two cells or two locations, novosparc computes the shortest path in kNearest Neighbor (kNN) graph.

Here we see that although the correlation between location and expression distances improves, it is still poor. Therefore, denovo reconstruction is failing.

Setting up for reconstruction ... done ( 0.3 seconds )

Reconstruction Only with Markers¶

Here we are going to reconstruct only with markers, first using a single marker we know and then randomly choosing a marker. In order to compare and evaluate the results we are going to look at the median (over all genes) of the correlation between a gene's true and predicted expression. Note that this is a naive evaluatino just for demonstration but more appropriate evaluations such as spatial correlation (cross Moran's I) are available.
